articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan said he would try to facilitate the parliamentary ratification of Sweden's NATO membership as much as possible, but added that Stockhom had still not taken sufficient action on Kurdish militants.
articles.title: Erdogan says he will try to facilitate Sweden's NATO bid ratification

articles.author: Karen Lema
articles.description: Japanese Prime Minister Fumio Kishida said on Saturday his country, the Philippines and the United States were cooperating to protect the freedom of the South China Sea as he committed to help enhance Manila's security capabilities.
articles.title: Japan PM Kishida: cooperating with Philippines, US to protect South China Sea

articles.author: Gibran Peshimam
articles.description: Nine Islamist militants attacked an air force training base in the central Pakistani area of Mianwali on Saturday damaging three "non-operational" aircraft, the military said, adding that all assailants had been killed by security forces.
articles.title: Militants attack air force base in central Pakistan, says military

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: The Philippines' National Security Adviser on Saturday rejected talk of a plot to destabilise the government of President Ferdinand Marcos Jr, saying the military and entire security sector were loyal to the commander-in-chief.
articles.title: Philippines military remains loyal to the president - national security adviser

articles.author: Saliou Samb
articles.description: The former head of Guinea's 2008 military junta, Moussa Dadis Camara, was sprung from prison by heavily armed men in Conakry in the early hours of Saturday along with three other high-ranking officers, Justice Minister Charles Wright said.
articles.title: Armed men spring Guinea's ex-junta leader Camara out of prison - minister

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: India's air safety watchdog proposes reduced night work hours and more rest for pilots, among measures to address rising complaints of pilot fatigue, according to draft regulations seen by Reuters on Saturday.
articles.title: India's aviation watchdog proposes less work, more rest for pilots - draft

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: European Commission President Ursula von der Leyen arrived in Kyiv on Saturday ahead of a report the European Union is expected to present next week about Ukraine's progress in its membership bid, a Ukrainian lawmaker said.
articles.title: EU's von der Leyen visits Kyiv ahead of report on accession progress

articles.author: Nidal Al-Mughrabi, Simon Lewis, Suleiman Al-Khalidi
articles.description: Gaza health officials said 15 people were killed in an Israeli air strike on an ambulance that the military said targeted Hamas militants, and Washington's top diplomat was due to hear Arab demands for a ceasefire in a meeting on Saturday in Jordan.
articles.title: US, Arab leaders to meet over Gaza as Palestinian deaths mount

articles.author: Gopal Sharma
articles.description: Rescue workers in Nepal began digging through the rubble of collapsed houses with their hands on Saturday, searching for survivors after the country's worst earthquake in eight years killed 137 people and shook buildings as far away as New Delhi.
articles.title: Rescuers struggle to find Nepal quake survivors, deaths at 137

articles.author: Andrew Chung
articles.description: The U.S. Supreme Court on Friday trained its sights once again on gun rights, agreeing to decide the legality of a federal ban imposed under former President Donald Trump on "bump stock" devices that enable semiautomatic weapons to fire like machine guns.
articles.title: US Supreme Court to decide legality of federal ban on gun 'bump stocks'
